        -:   38:/** \class CwiseUnaryOp
        -:   39:  * \ingroup Core_Module
        -:   40:  *
        -:   41:  * \brief Generic expression where a coefficient-wise unary operator is applied to an expression
        -:   42:  *
        -:   43:  * \tparam UnaryOp template functor implementing the operator
        -:   44:  * \tparam XprType the type of the expression to which we are applying the unary operator
        -:   45:  *
        -:   46:  * This class represents an expression where a unary operator is applied to an expression.
        -:   47:  * It is the return type of all operations taking exactly 1 input expression, regardless of the
        -:   48:  * presence of other inputs such as scalars. For example, the operator* in the expression 3*matrix
        -:   49:  * is considered unary, because only the right-hand side is an expression, and its
        -:   50:  * return type is a specialization of CwiseUnaryOp.
        -:   51:  *
        -:   52:  * Most of the time, this is the only way that it is used, so you typically don't have to name
        -:   53:  * CwiseUnaryOp types explicitly.
        -:   54:  *
        -:   55:  * \sa MatrixBase::unaryExpr(const CustomUnaryOp &) const, class CwiseBinaryOp, class CwiseNullaryOp
        -:   56:  */
        -:   57:template<typename UnaryOp, typename XprType>
        -:   58:class CwiseUnaryOp : public CwiseUnaryOpImpl<UnaryOp, XprType, typename internal::traits<XprType>::StorageKind>, internal::no_assignment_operator
        -:   59:{
        -:   60:  public:
        -:   61:
